Great question — no MySQL needed. WordPress has a built-in system for this called post meta, and it's the standard way to store extra data against any post.

Here's how it works:

WordPress has a table called wp_postmeta that stores key-value pairs attached to any post. It looks like this:

post_id	meta_key	meta_value
42	_ak_price	450000
42	_ak_bedrooms	4
42	_ak_bathrooms	2
42	_ak_sqft	2100
WordPress gives us two functions to work with it:

update_post_meta( $post_id, '_ak_price', '450000' ) — saves a value
get_post_meta( $post_id, '_ak_price', true ) — reads it back
No custom tables, no raw SQL, no MySQL queries. WordPress handles all of that for us under the hood. The underscore prefix on _ak_price is a convention that hides the fields from the default custom fields UI, keeping things clean.

